u"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-10-peculiarities-of-cutting-the-bottom-part-of-the-fishtail-skirt/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-10-peculiarities-of-cutting-the-bottom-part-of-the-fishtail-skirt/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T16:58:14+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:46:05+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 10. Peculiarities of Cutting the Bottom Part of the Fishtail Skirt."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 10. Peculiarities of Cutting the Bottom Part of the Fishtail Skirt."><meta itemprop="description" content="You can see the side seam in the middle, the central back seam on the left, and the central front fold line on the right."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 10. Peculiarities of Cutting the Bottom Part of the Fishtail Skirt.</h1><p><strong>I have outlined our mock-up bottom piece on the writing board. </strong></p><p><strong>You can see the side seam in the middle, the central back seam on the left, and the central front fold line on the right. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The front fold line and the central back line must be parallel to the lengthwise grain.</strong></p><p><strong>There is another important recommendation. </strong></p><p><strong>If the bottom part of your skirt with a train is even wider and longer, </strong>then the side seam edge will be cut on the bias with the central back edge positioned along the lengthwise grain.</p><p><strong>In that case, </strong>the area around the bias-cut side seam edge will not only stretch out, but get deformed significantly and change its shape. The fabric will get stretched out and the piece will become narrower.</p><p><strong>This can be critical for large garments with much volume! </strong>I have had cases when a large fabric casing cut in this manner refused to fit the petticoat it was sewn for just because it was stretched out and deformed.</p><p><strong>For this reason, I recommend you should divide such large pieces in segments or gores and cut them strictly on the lengthwise grain as well. </strong></p><p><strong>I have roughly divided the back piece in segments and marked the supposed direction of lengthwise grain on them (see below). </strong>The lengthwise grain will support the bias areas of these small segments.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Of course, you normally divide the back piece in segments on skirts which are part of some kind of inner construction: </strong>such as, for example, a lining or a base for decorative elements.</p><p><strong>We need to account for a range of factors for every new garment, size, and fabric. </strong>Suppose your face fabric is very prone to deformation along the bias grain, or maybe it is rather loosely woven and soft and does not hold its shape so well. If that is the case, you had better replace it. If you cannot replace it, you will have to think over how to decorate the garment to use those back gores to the best effect.</p><p><strong>For example, you can use decorative lace inserts if you need to divide in gores a skirt made of lightweight chiffon.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Do not be afraid of going creative. Try different ideas! </strong>The ones I am suggesting are not the only solution!</p><p><strong>Let us make a small summary. </strong></p><p><strong>I have explained how to design a skirt with a train when the seam joining the top with the bottom runs at an angle. </strong>The same principle may be used for designing skirts with decorative inserts, ruffles, etc. A half-scale mock-up gives you a full picture of the future garment with respect to all dimensions and parameters. You will no longer have to think over what shape and length to give the train to make it proportionate to your client’s body.</p><p><strong>A finished mock-up bottom part of your skirt </strong>simultaneously provides you with a pattern of the bottom part of your petticoat of the desired shape.</p><p><strong>And the top piece </strong>left on the dress-form after separating the bottom part is more than just a mock-up and pattern for cutting and sewing the top part of your skirt. It is at the same time a mock-up and pattern for making the top part of your petticoat.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>At this stage, </strong>you can use the resulting patterns to sew a half-scale mock-up petticoat (if you still have any doubts) or start sewing a full-scale petticoat.</p><p>Of course, I was doing everything rather roughly and quickly because my goal was to explain the point behind the technique. When you start doing the same things in practice, you should indeed take your time and be very accurate!</p><p><strong>After separating the bottom part, you should carefully transfer it on a piece of paper and measure it. </strong>It is very easy to scale up a pattern like this! If you know how to use Photoshop, you will simply scan the resulting pattern, double its size, and print it out to get a full-size pattern. It is exactly how I do it. You can also double the size of the initial drawing without computer by using square paper.</p><p><strong>And now I would like to make an additional comment on adjusting the resulting pattern after client’s measurements. </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose you have adjusted the gores of the bottom part of the skirt and made them narrower.</strong> You must apply the same adjustments to the corresponding areas of the top part of the skirt. When working with the mock-up, we marked points along the separating line for aligning the top with the bottom. These points will help you align the pieces and easily find the areas of the top part which require the same adjustments. You will always be able to see how the pieces align. And this will allow you to adjust the joining edges in a neat and proportionate way.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>How come I recommend you sew the petticoat using the same top and bottom patterns you got for the skirt? </strong></p><p><strong>The thing is that the seam joining the top and the bottom of the petticoat must fully coincide with the seam joining the top and the bottom of the skirt. </strong>If you happen to use a petticoat with a strictly horizontal joining seam for a skirt with an inclined joining seam, you will inevitably have to adjust some or other parts of the skirt. The skirt will never acquire the desired shape unless its inner construction has the same silhouette.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2010.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I hope you can now appreciate the advantages of the mock-up method. </strong>If not for this method, you would have to spend a fair bit of time thinking over many issues: how to give the right incline to the seam joining the top with the bottom, how long to make the train, what shape to give the bottom part of the skirt to make the fabric settle in a graceful way. Imagine how many hours it spares you!</p><p>It has taken me exactly 50cm of leftover fabric to sew our mock-up skirt. This method is rather budget-friendly. I will show you some more examples of skirts made based on the same principle.</p><p><strong>I am absolutely sure that you will use the mock-up method very widely! </strong>You would not be able to construct the bottom part (your petticoat) correctly without sewing a mock-up. Moreover, you would get as many questions as when working on the skirt itself. The mock-up method allows you to solve lots of potential issues in one go and within a short time.</p><p><strong>In conclusion, I would like to say </strong>that, if you want to put ruffles on your skirt, it will be a lot easier to draw the layout and calculate all proportions and amounts of necessary elements on a small half-scale pattern than on a large piece of fabric where it is hard to focus on separate details. After polishing it up on a mock-up, you can safely transfer it on a large full-scale piece!</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></st